    "## 10. Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Predictive methods (Lasso, SHAP, RF) optimise in-distribution accuracy** but include spurious correlates that degrade under shift.\n",
    "2. **Causal methods (ICP, PC) sacrifice some in-distribution accuracy** for robustness — the performance gap narrows and reverses as shift severity increases.\n",
    "3. **The crossover point** (where causal features outperform predictive) depends on shift severity. For most real-world deployments with meaningful shift, this crossover occurs at moderate severity.\n",
    "4. **The blended approach** (consensus: causal ∩ predictive) captures both robustness and accuracy. This is the recommended default for production.\n",
    "5. **Monitoring set:** Features in predictive selection but not causal selection should be tracked for distribution drift. When they start degrading, fall back to the causal feature set.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Production Decision Framework\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Is distribution shift a concern?\n",
    "├── No → Use predictive selection (Lasso, SHAP, GA)\n",
    "└── Yes → Do you have multiple genuine environments?\n",
    "    ├── Yes → Run ICP + blend with predictive selection\n",
    "    └── No → Run DML/causal forests + use causal importance scores\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### References\n",
    "- Peters, J., Bühlmann, P., & Meinshausen, N. (2016). JRSS-B, 78(5), 947–1012.\n",
    "- Chernozhukov, V., et al. (2018). *Econometrics Journal*, 21(1), C1–C68.\n",
    "- Athey, S., Tibshirani, J., & Wager, S. (2019). *Annals of Statistics*, 47(2), 1148–1178."
